NYC Taxicab Analysis¶

The data covers green taxicab trips during March 2020. In the analysis below, parts 1-4 consist of data exploration, parts 5-6 consist of tip percentage modelling, and part 7 provides geospatial visualizations about taxi dropoffs.

Part 1¶

The code chunk below imports trip data from the NYC TLC, imports demographic information by taxi zone, and merges the demographic information to the taxi ride dataset. I assume we will want to include demographic information about the pickup (PU) and dropoff (DO) zones, so I merge the demographic information on the main dataset twice. The merged dataset representing trips in March 2020 has 223,496 rows.

# Read in taxicab and demographic data
taxi_rides = pd.read_parquet("https://s3.amazonaws.com/nyc-tlc/trip+data/green_tripdata_2020-03.parquet")
demographic_info = pd.read_csv("data/raw/taxi_zone_demographics.csv")
demographic_info.drop(columns = ["Unnamed: 0"], axis = 1, inplace = True)

# Merge taxi ride and demographic data./
    # We will merge twice, first to include the demographic information of the taximeter engage zone, 
    # and second to include the demographic information of the taximeter disengage zone.
departure_zone = demographic_info.copy()
departure_zone.columns = [col + "_PU" for col in departure_zone.columns]
departure_zone.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)

arrival_zone = demographic_info.copy()
arrival_zone.columns = [col + "_DO" for col in arrival_zone.columns]
arrival_zone.reset_index(drop = True, inplace = True)

taxi_rides_merged = pd.merge(left = taxi_rides, right = departure_zone, how = "left", left_on = "PULocationID", right_on = "Taxi zone_PU")
taxi_rides_merged = pd.merge(left = taxi_rides_merged, right = arrival_zone, how = "left", left_on = "DOLocationID", right_on = "Taxi zone_DO")

# Print out the rows and columns of each dataframe

Part 3¶

The code below describes trips by hour and day of the week. Most pickups and dropoffs occur on Mondays (day = 0). Most pickups occur from 3pm-5pm, and most dropoffs occur from 4pm-6pm. This result makes sense, as we might expect for most taxi rides to occur during evening rush hour/early evening. Looking at the summary stastics, the hour 4pm and day of week Wednesday (day = 2) both have the highest average trip distances for both pickups and dropoffs.

Part 4¶

I used the taxi zone lookup file under data/raw to determine which taxi zones corresponded to airports. ID 132 is JFK, 138 is LaGuardia, 1 is EWR/Newark Airport. In March 2020, a little over 2,700 trips began or ended at one of the three airports. I observe far more airport dropoffs than pickups. Most dropoffs appear to occur around 3pm-5pm, and most pickups appear to occur around 6am and 3-4pm. Airport trips tend to have higher fares on average, at a mean of 25 dollars versus a 14-dollar average fare for all trips.

I was curious about whether airport trips declined sharply when the pandemic began. The last histogram visualizes dropoffs by day. Most of the dropoffs occured on March 5, and I observe a sharp decline in airport dropoffs after March 20.

# Run and evaluate a very basic gradient boosting regressor

# Drop missing values, leaving roughly half the records. Because we explicitly want to investigate demographic information in the next section, I do not want to impute demographic 
    # information and potentially introduce misleading data to the dataset.
taxi_rides_ml = taxi_rides_ml.dropna()
taxi_rides_ml.shape

taxi_rides_ml = taxi_rides_ml.sample(frac = 1) # shuffle the dataset to ensure the algorithm is not merely memorizing the data
X, y = taxi_rides_ml.drop(columns = ["tip_percentage"], axis = 1), taxi_rides_ml[["tip_percentage"]]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, train_size = 0.7, random_state=123)

estimator = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators = 250, random_state=123)

estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = estimator.predict(X_test)

print(f"The baseline model's R2 score is {r2_score(y_test, y_pred)} and its mean absolute error is {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)}.")

Part 6¶

The next code chunks evaluate the results by pickup and dropoff location demographics. I look first at the distribution of the black and nonwhite population in pickup and dropoff zones. Then, I set a threshold where the population rates are greater than the median. I analyze the average tip percentage and model error above and below this threshold. The results appear to show that predicted tip percentages in general are lower in zones with Black and Hispanic population rates that are higher than the median. Additionally, the mean absolute error is higher for high-Black population pickup zones.

In [20]:
# Set up thresholds (at equal to or greater than the median)
comparison_dataset = X_test.copy()

comparison_dataset["BlackPU_Threshold"] = np.where(comparison_dataset["BlackNonHisp_PU"] >= comparison_dataset["BlackNonHisp_PU"].median(), 1, 0)
comparison_dataset["HispanicPU_Threshold"] = np.where(comparison_dataset["Hispanic_PU"] >= comparison_dataset["Hispanic_PU"].median(), 1, 0)
comparison_dataset["HispanicDO_Threshold"] = np.where(comparison_dataset["Hispanic_DO"] >= comparison_dataset["Hispanic_DO"].median(), 1, 0)
comparison_dataset["BlackDO_Threshold"] = np.where(comparison_dataset["BlackNonHisp_DO"] >= comparison_dataset["BlackNonHisp_DO"].median(), 1, 0)

# Merge predictions and calculate MAE for each row
taxi_rides_ml_merged = pd.concat([comparison_dataset.reset_index(drop=True), y_test.reset_index(drop = True), pd.DataFrame({"predicted_tip_pct": y_pred})], axis = 1)

taxi_rides_ml_merged["mae"] = taxi_rides_ml_merged.apply(lambda row: mean_absolute_error([row.tip_percentage], [row.predicted_tip_pct] ), axis = 1)

Part 7¶

In the cells below, I use the geopandas package to visualize dropoffs across NYC. As should be expected, most dropoffs occur in Manhattan, and Queens near LaGuardia is the second-most common dropoff location. I was suprised to see that not as many dropoffs occurred in the JFK area as near LaGuardia. I also looked at the number of trips after March 11, 2020, as this is the day that the WHO declared the COVID-19 pandemic. I expect to see trips decline after this date. As anticipated, the maximum number of dropoffs declined by a significant amount.
